	abstract = {This case study investigates how technology, particularly the Classkick platform, is integrated into primary school English as a Foreign Language (EFL) classes to develop students' academic participation, engagement and achievement. The study examines the effect of Classkick on public school grade five students and 10 teachers through a mixed-methods approach. Findings showcase that the interactive elements, real-time responses, and comprehensible user interface considerably enhanced students' motives, self-confidence using the tool, and cooperative learning. Classkick supports promoting an active, student-centred learning environment. The findings indicate that Classkick can transform traditional EFL teaching and learning, and support in-depth understanding of more impactful learning experiences, with vast significance for the future of computer assisted language learning. © 2025 by IGI Global Scientific Publishing.},
